<TITLE> Norway says Madagascar aid freeze in force </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 ANTANANARIVO, Thu Mar 19,(bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Norway said on Thursday its aid freeze slapped on Madagascar earlier this week remained in force under the new government of President Andry Rajoelina whose rise to power has drawn international disapproval. Norway, which gives 90 million crowns ($13.84 million) in annual aid, appears to be the only nation to have publicly announced an aid freeze despite threats from other countries during Madagascar's recent political crisis. Rajoelina, who at 34 is Africa's youngest president, took power on Tuesday after leading opposition street protests against President Marc Ravalomanana since the start of this year. Ravalomanana handed over to the military, and they in turn conferred power on Rajoelina. Norway's foreign ministry announced the aid freeze on the same day that happened, some hours before. It said in a statement on Tuesday that "a number of other donor countries" had taken the same step. "The actual decision was made before the change of president because of the unstable situation during the last days before the change," ministry spokeswoman Ragnhild Simenstad said on Thursday. "It probably will be in force until we assess the situation further." Though Madagascar's Constitutional Court has endorsed Rajoelina's takeover, various world bodies including the African Union (AU) and United Nations (UN) have expressed concern at the change in leadership without a vote. Zambia wants Madagascar suspended from southern African trade bloc SADC and th
